## Groups whose Sylow subgroups are cyclic

In the study of **finite groups** (/Finite_group), a **Z‑group** is a finite group whose **[Sylow subgroup](/Sylow_subgroup)**es are all **[cyclic](/Cyclic_group)**.  The letter “Z” originates from the German word *zyklisch* (cyclic) and also reflects the historical classification of these groups in the work of Hans Zassenhaus (1935).  In many modern textbooks these groups are simply called **metacyclic groups**, though that term now carries a broader meaning that includes non‑cyclic \(p\)-groups; see **[Metacyclic group](/Metacyclic_group)** for the contemporary definition, which is stricter in the classical context.

Every group whose Sylow subgroups are cyclic is itself **[metacyclic](/Metacyclic_group)**, and consequently **[supersolvable](/Supersolvable_group)**.  Such a group possesses a cyclic **[derived subgroup](/Derived_subgroup)** with a cyclic maximal abelian quotient.  A typical presentation, due to Hall (1959, Th. 9.4.3), is

\[
G(m,n,r)=\langle a,b\mid a^{m}=b^{n}=1,\; bab^{-1}=a^{r}\rangle,
\]

where \(mn\) is the order of \(G\), \(\gcd\big((r-1)n,m\big)=1\), and \(r^{n}\equiv1\pmod m\).  The character theory of Z‑groups is well understood (see [Çelik 1976](/Çelik_1976)), as they are **[monomial groups](/Monomial_group)**.  Moreover, the derived length of any Z‑group is at most 2, which makes them a natural testing ground for deeper results in solvable group theory.

The class can be generalized in several directions.  Hall introduced **[A‑groups](/A-group)**, those groups whose Sylow subgroups are abelian; these groups may have arbitrarily large derived length (Hall 1940).  Suzuki (1955) relaxed the condition on the Sylow‑2 subgroup, allowing dihedral and generalized quaternion groups in addition to cyclic ones.  These generalizations broaden the scope of Z‑groups while preserving many of their nice structural features.

### Key properties

* **Cyclic Sylow subgroups** – every Sylow \(p\)-subgroup is generated by a single element.  
* **Metacyclic structure** – the group can be generated by two elements, one of which normalizes the other via an automorphism of prime power order.  
* **Supersolvability** – every chief factor is cyclic of prime order, ensuring a refined series of normal subgroups.  
* **Monomial representation** – every irreducible complex character is induced from a linear character of a subgroup.  

These properties make Z‑groups a cornerstone in the classification of finite solvable groups and provide a fertile ground for applications in algebraic combinatorics and Galois theory.

## Group with a generalized central series

The definition of **[central series](/Central_series)** used for Z‑groups is somewhat technical.  A series of a group \(G\) is a collection \(S\) of subgroups of \(G\), linearly ordered by inclusion, such that for every \(g\in G\) the subgroups

\[
A_{g}=\bigcap\{N\in S\mid g\in N\},\qquad 
B_{g}= \bigcup\{N\in S\mid g\notin N\}
\]

are both members of \(S\).  A (generalized) central series of \(G\) is a series with the additional requirement that every \(N\in S\) is normal in \(G\) and that for each \(g\in G\) the quotient \(A_{g}/B_{g}\) lies inside the center of \(G/B_{g}\).  A **Z‑group** is precisely a group that admits such a series.

Examples include the **[hypercentral groups](/Hypercentral_group)**, whose transfinite upper central series forms a central series, and the **[hypocentral groups](/Hypocentral_group)**, whose transfinite lower central series does the same.  These groups illustrate how the abstract central‑series condition can be realized in both finite and infinite settings, and they provide a natural bridge between the finite‑group definition and the ordered‑group version.

The generalized central series is closely related to other filtrations such as the **upper central series**, **lower central series**, and **derived series**, but its defining property — that each factor \(A_{g}/B_{g}\) sits in the center of the corresponding quotient — gives Z‑groups a distinctive combinatorial flavor.  This flavor is exploited in the study of **ordered groups** (/Ordered_group), where the series interacts with the order topology in a manner reminiscent of the discrete ordering of the integers.

### Connection to ordered groups

In the realm of **[ordered groups](/Ordered_group)**, a **Z‑group** (or \(\mathbb Z\)-group) is a discretely ordered abelian group whose quotient over its minimal convex subgroup is divisible.  Such groups are elementarily equivalent to the standard integer group \((\mathbb Z,+,<)\) and therefore serve as a model-theoretic analogue of the familiar arithmetic of the integers.  This ordered‑group perspective is formalized in the article **[Presburger arithmetic](/Presburger_arithmetic)**, where Z‑groups provide an alternative presentation of the same logical theory.

The ordered‑group definition highlights the versatility of the Z‑group concept: it appears not only in pure group theory but also in model theory, lattice theory, and even in the study of topological groups.  The interplay between algebraic structure and order makes Z‑groups a rich subject for cross‑disciplinary research.

## Special 2‑transitive groups

A **[Z‑group]** (note the hyphen) is a group faithfully represented as a **[doubly transitive permutation group](/Doubly_transitive_permutation_group)** in which no non‑identity element fixes more than two points.  When such a group also satisfies additional parity conditions — specifically, when it is of odd degree and is not a **[Frobenius group](/Frobenius_group)** — it is termed a **(ZT)-group**, and these are precisely the **[Zassenhaus groups](/Zassenhaus_group)** of odd degree.  Classical examples include the projective special linear groups \(\operatorname{PSL}(2,2k+1)\) and the Suzuki groups \(\operatorname{Sz}(2^{2k+1})\) for any positive integer \(k\).

The study of these 2‑transitive Z‑groups reveals deep connections between permutation representations, finite geometry, and the theory of **simple groups**.  Because they are sharply constrained by the “at most two fixed points” condition, Zassenhaus groups exhibit a remarkable rigidity that has been exploited in the classification of finite simple groups.  Their structure often mirrors that of the projective linear groups, yet they possess unique combinatorial properties that set them apart.

### Examples and significance

* **Projective special linear groups** \(\operatorname{PSL}(2,q)\) with \(q\) odd act doubly transitively on the projective line and satisfy the Z‑group condition.  
* **Suzuki groups** \(\operatorname{Sz}(2^{2k+1})\) are the namesake examples, named after Michio Suzuki, and they provide the odd‑degree Zassenhaus groups that are not Frobenius.  
* These groups are closely linked to **generalized quadrangles** and **Hall–Janko** type geometries, illustrating how permutation constraints can generate rich algebraic and combinatorial structures.

The classification of Z‑groups in the permutation setting continues to be an active area of research, especially in the context of modern developments such as **automorphism group computations** and **computational group theory**.